WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.649 --> 00:00:02.440
ADRIAN ROSELLI: Hi.

00:00:02.440 --> 00:00:03.270
I'm Adrian Roselli.

00:00:03.270 --> 00:00:06.960
You might have seen pictures
of me around the office.

00:00:06.960 --> 00:00:08.710
I'm sorry.

00:00:08.710 --> 00:00:10.420
I'm here to talk
about accessibility,

00:00:10.420 --> 00:00:13.800
but I have two slides
dedicated to my ego.

00:00:13.800 --> 00:00:16.140
One of them says, look,
I've written some stuff.

00:00:16.140 --> 00:00:18.090
Good for me.

00:00:18.090 --> 00:00:21.660
Another one says that I work
with the HTML Working Group

00:00:21.660 --> 00:00:23.630
from the W3C.

00:00:23.630 --> 00:00:26.400
I'm on the Accessibility
Task Force.

00:00:26.400 --> 00:00:28.670
I've been building
for the web since '94,

00:00:28.670 --> 00:00:30.860
so almost since the
start of the web.

00:00:30.860 --> 00:00:34.240
I have a software development
company, Algonquin, which

00:00:34.240 --> 00:00:36.540
I co-founded 18 years ago.

00:00:36.540 --> 00:00:39.210
I have a website, which
is crazy nowadays, right?

00:00:39.210 --> 00:00:41.562
I have a website at
AdrianRoselli.com,

00:00:41.562 --> 00:00:46.470
and you can avoid-slash-follow
me on Twitter @aardrian.

00:00:46.470 --> 00:00:48.590
I think that's how
it's pronounced.

00:00:48.590 --> 00:00:50.930
You shouldn't have to say
your Twitter handle out loud.

00:00:50.930 --> 00:00:51.770
I know.

00:00:51.770 --> 00:00:56.480
So to dive right in, if you have
been on the internet, if you

00:00:56.480 --> 00:00:59.250
have been using Twitter,
mailing lists, et cetera,

00:00:59.250 --> 00:01:02.180
you might have seen a11y.

00:01:02.180 --> 00:01:05.930
a11y is a numeronym, and
it means accessibility.

00:01:05.930 --> 00:01:09.110
Essentially all it does it
takes the A first letter, the Y

00:01:09.110 --> 00:01:11.039
last letter, replaces
all the letters

00:01:11.039 --> 00:01:12.580
in between with a
number representing

00:01:12.580 --> 00:01:15.020
the number of characters
that have been excised.

00:01:15.020 --> 00:01:18.180
So localization is l10n.

00:01:18.180 --> 00:01:21.000
Internationalization is i18n.

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:22.870
This is really
popular on Twitter

00:01:22.870 --> 00:01:27.140
because it's working in your
favor for character limits.

00:01:27.140 --> 00:01:30.502
It's also a great way with
the hashtag, the a11y hashtag,

00:01:30.502 --> 00:01:32.210
to see what people
are talking about that

00:01:32.210 --> 00:01:33.251
is accessibility-related.

00:01:36.620 --> 00:01:39.711
I often talk about how
accessibility gets no respect.

00:01:39.711 --> 00:01:41.710
We'll be talking about
it in the software world,

00:01:41.710 --> 00:01:44.950
but I'd like to point out
here in the day-to-day world.

00:01:44.950 --> 00:01:46.980
So we've been
redoing our office.

00:01:46.980 --> 00:01:49.330
That's not the furniture
we have right now,

00:01:49.330 --> 00:01:51.950
but the furniture we have now
blocked too many of the colors.

00:01:51.950 --> 00:01:56.430
So we have these three colors
that we've been very fond of,

00:01:56.430 --> 00:01:58.820
this gray, this
green, and this blue.

00:01:58.820 --> 00:02:00.450
The green is called Lime Ricky.

00:02:00.450 --> 00:02:04.210
The blue is called Online,
because that's a cool name.

00:02:04.210 --> 00:02:06.890
And the gray of the ceiling
is called Cyberspace.

00:02:06.890 --> 00:02:08.610
So Sherwin Williams
seemed to think

00:02:08.610 --> 00:02:13.240
that these were a great set of
names for colors, so much so

00:02:13.240 --> 00:02:16.750
that when it came time to choose
what they were going to name

00:02:16.750 --> 00:02:20.250
the color of putty-- it's
like the '80s IBM desktop

00:02:20.250 --> 00:02:23.110
computers-- Accessible Beige.

00:02:23.110 --> 00:02:24.910
So the concept of
accessibility getting

00:02:24.910 --> 00:02:26.670
respect outside of
the software world,

00:02:26.670 --> 00:02:29.870
yeah, it carries through
to paint colors as well.

00:02:29.870 --> 00:02:31.840
So sort of keep that
in the back your head.

00:02:31.840 --> 00:02:35.700
You might sort of run across
this trend in the real world

00:02:35.700 --> 00:02:37.870
in other places as well.

00:02:37.870 --> 00:02:40.360
We are going to go
over some statistics.

00:02:40.360 --> 00:02:43.960
I'm going to pitch to you
the idea of being selfish.

00:02:43.960 --> 00:02:46.600
I'll go through some
techniques, basic tests

00:02:46.600 --> 00:02:49.800
that you can run yourself.

00:02:49.800 --> 00:02:52.100
For those who are
technical, I'll

00:02:52.100 --> 00:02:55.500
even talk a little bit about
ARIA and HTML best practices.

00:02:55.500 --> 00:02:57.670
If you're not technical,
we can breeze through that.

00:02:57.670 --> 00:03:01.130
I am available for questions,
here and on the internet.

00:03:01.130 --> 00:03:03.610
And then I'll have
some links at the end.

00:03:03.610 --> 00:03:06.570
So to dive right
into the statistics,

00:03:06.570 --> 00:03:08.660
not always super
exciting, but it's

00:03:08.660 --> 00:03:10.870
good to know what these
numbers look like.

00:03:10.870 --> 00:03:14.600
In the United States in
the 21 to 64 age bracket,

00:03:14.600 --> 00:03:16.480
we're looking at
a population of 10

00:03:16.480 --> 00:03:20.860
and 1/2 percent that have
some form of a disability.

00:03:20.860 --> 00:03:23.660
As you hit the 65 to
74-year-old age group,

00:03:23.660 --> 00:03:25.780
you're talking about a
quarter of the population.

00:03:25.780 --> 00:03:29.360
When you get above 75, that's
half of the US population

00:03:29.360 --> 00:03:32.010
has some form of disability.

00:03:32.010 --> 00:03:34.370
These do include
visual disabilities,

00:03:34.370 --> 00:03:36.870
visual impairments, hearing
impairments, mobility,

00:03:36.870 --> 00:03:41.660
cognitive, and then the various
flavors of those as well.

00:03:41.660 --> 00:03:46.520
For vision impairments,
Americans from just under 2%

00:03:46.520 --> 00:03:50.620
in the 21-64 age bracket up
to about 10% of the population

00:03:50.620 --> 00:03:52.560
when you get 75 and up.

00:03:52.560 --> 00:03:56.330
Worldwide, we're talking
about 285 million people.

00:03:56.330 --> 00:03:57.730
39 million of those are blind.

00:04:01.200 --> 00:04:06.610
For hearing loss, in the 45
to 64-year-old age group,

00:04:06.610 --> 00:04:09.049
almost 20% of the population
has some hearing loss.

00:04:09.049 --> 00:04:11.590
When you get above 75 years old,
you're looking at about half

00:04:11.590 --> 00:04:14.780
of the population, half
of the US population.

00:04:14.780 --> 00:04:19.190
Worldwide, 360 million people
have disabling hearing loss.

00:04:19.190 --> 00:04:22.460
I gave a talk at Accessibility
Camp New York City

00:04:22.460 --> 00:04:24.340
a couple weeks ago,
or a few weeks ago,

00:04:24.340 --> 00:04:27.160
and there was a woman who said
my statistics are out of date.

00:04:27.160 --> 00:04:29.440
I haven't been able to
validate the new numbers.

00:04:29.440 --> 00:04:33.130
But she says that it's 360
million people worldwide.

00:04:33.130 --> 00:04:35.560
It's closer to about
500 million people.

00:04:35.560 --> 00:04:39.550
So these numbers might
even be an underestimation.

00:04:39.550 --> 00:04:43.100
Mobility impairments-- 21
to 64-year-old age group

00:04:43.100 --> 00:04:44.660
is almost 6%.

00:04:44.660 --> 00:04:47.990
75 and up age group, a
third of the population

00:04:47.990 --> 00:04:51.620
has some form of
mobility impairment.

00:04:51.620 --> 00:04:53.680
Cognitive impairments,
which can include things

00:04:53.680 --> 00:04:56.210
like dyslexia,
dyscalculia, which

00:04:56.210 --> 00:05:00.430
is sort of the numbers version
of dyslexia, memory issues,

00:05:00.430 --> 00:05:04.680
ADD, ADHD, et cetera,
there's a pretty broad range.

00:05:04.680 --> 00:05:09.510
You're looking at 4.3% in
the younger age bracket,

00:05:09.510 --> 00:05:13.460
up to 14+% in the
75-and-up age bracket.

00:05:13.460 --> 00:05:14.954
There's a trend
with these numbers

00:05:14.954 --> 00:05:16.370
that I think you've
probably seen,

00:05:16.370 --> 00:05:20.840
is that that number tends to
increase as the age increases.

00:05:20.840 --> 00:05:22.510
So I've given you
the statistics,

00:05:22.510 --> 00:05:24.660
and statistics really
don't sell people

00:05:24.660 --> 00:05:26.520
on why they need to
support accessibility.

00:05:26.520 --> 00:05:28.080
Raw numbers are
just raw numbers.

00:05:28.080 --> 00:05:30.650
They don't always
get the point across.

00:05:30.650 --> 00:05:32.910
So I'm going to preach to
you on how to be selfish

00:05:32.910 --> 00:05:35.080
and how this can be good.

00:05:35.080 --> 00:05:38.540
Web Accessibility In Mind
has this wonderful hierarchy

00:05:38.540 --> 00:05:42.770
for motivating accessibility
change within an organization.

00:05:42.770 --> 00:05:44.350
At the bottom of
their pyramid, they

00:05:44.350 --> 00:05:48.290
have guilt. You can guilt
people to support accessibility.

00:05:48.290 --> 00:05:50.160
Then you can start
to punish them.

00:05:50.160 --> 00:05:51.890
You can make it a requirement.

00:05:51.890 --> 00:05:55.150
You can work to reward
them, enlighten them,

00:05:55.150 --> 00:05:56.910
and ultimately, you
want to inspire them.

00:05:56.910 --> 00:05:59.493
You want people to feel inspired
so that they'll support users

00:05:59.493 --> 00:06:00.390
with disabilities.

00:06:00.390 --> 00:06:01.640
I think this is a great model.

00:06:01.640 --> 00:06:03.500
I think it falls short.

00:06:03.500 --> 00:06:06.020
I think that we can modify this.

00:06:06.020 --> 00:06:09.300
And the star on top of this
thing is to make it about me.

00:06:09.300 --> 00:06:11.580
If you start to look at
it as how it affects you,

00:06:11.580 --> 00:06:16.980
you might start to accidentally
support some disabilities.

00:06:16.980 --> 00:06:20.080
So getting older-- as I was
doing the opening numbers,

00:06:20.080 --> 00:06:21.914
you saw the numbers
of people who

00:06:21.914 --> 00:06:23.580
are affected with
different disabilities

00:06:23.580 --> 00:06:26.120
tends to decline as people age.

00:06:26.120 --> 00:06:28.029
Getting older does
affect nearly everybody.

00:06:28.029 --> 00:06:30.320
There are some people who
might be fortunate enough not

00:06:30.320 --> 00:06:30.862
to get older.

00:06:30.862 --> 00:06:33.195
Unless you're Superman, that
probably doesn't bode well.

00:06:33.195 --> 00:06:34.110
It means you're dead.

00:06:34.110 --> 00:06:37.100
It does, as I say, carry
risks and side effects,

00:06:37.100 --> 00:06:39.050
definitely not for the young.

00:06:39.050 --> 00:06:42.165
In this image, there are two
couples sitting on the curb.

00:06:42.165 --> 00:06:43.790
They're basically
doing the same thing.

00:06:43.790 --> 00:06:46.620
They might be debating
where to go for dinner.

00:06:46.620 --> 00:06:48.850
They might be looking at
what they want to do next.

00:06:48.850 --> 00:06:51.550
The only thing that's separating
them, besides about four feet,

00:06:51.550 --> 00:06:54.020
is probably 40 years in age.

00:06:54.020 --> 00:06:56.990
They're really the
same set of people,

00:06:56.990 --> 00:06:59.920
same objectives, same goals.

00:06:59.920 --> 00:07:01.380
Here we have two
women on a bench.

00:07:01.380 --> 00:07:02.344
They are both reading.

00:07:02.344 --> 00:07:04.260
They're separated by
about a foot and probably

00:07:04.260 --> 00:07:05.840
another 40 years.

00:07:05.840 --> 00:07:10.000
Also, one of them is our reading
off of a solar-powered device.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:11.280
The other one is not.

00:07:11.280 --> 00:07:12.730
That's hilarious.

00:07:12.730 --> 00:07:14.200
Are people laughing
on the hangout?

00:07:14.200 --> 00:07:14.700
No?

00:07:14.700 --> 00:07:15.832
OK.

00:07:15.832 --> 00:07:19.510
[SIGHS] Tough internet crowd.

00:07:19.510 --> 00:07:23.445
Accidents-- accidents
are a thing that happen.

00:07:23.445 --> 00:07:24.820
All of these listed
here are just

00:07:24.820 --> 00:07:26.890
examples of what's
happened to me--

00:07:26.890 --> 00:07:29.300
broken limbs, eye
injuries, hearing injuries,

00:07:29.300 --> 00:07:33.160
head trauma-- big
fan of head trauma.

00:07:33.160 --> 00:07:36.442
An example of somebody who
has their wrist in a cast.

00:07:36.442 --> 00:07:38.150
When you don't have
access to that wrist,

00:07:38.150 --> 00:07:40.441
it makes it a little bit hard
to type or use your mouse

00:07:40.441 --> 00:07:42.860
or do other
day-to-day activities.

00:07:42.860 --> 00:07:45.410
This can happen to anybody.

00:07:45.410 --> 00:07:46.950
You can have an
eye injury, which

00:07:46.950 --> 00:07:49.970
means now you're limited in
peripheral vision and binocular

00:07:49.970 --> 00:07:50.910
vision.

00:07:50.910 --> 00:07:53.360
Some people might do it
strictly for fashion.

00:07:53.360 --> 00:07:55.180
That's a personal choice.

00:07:55.180 --> 00:07:58.230
That is not me,
despite the hair.

00:07:58.230 --> 00:08:01.030
Some people are sort of
predisposed to circumstances.

00:08:01.030 --> 00:08:03.890
This is a scenario in
England where people chase

00:08:03.890 --> 00:08:06.894
a wheel of cheese down a hill.

00:08:06.894 --> 00:08:08.810
They're chasing a wheel
of cheese down a hill.

00:08:08.810 --> 00:08:10.340
At the bottom of
the hill, they have

00:08:10.340 --> 00:08:12.630
ambulances waiting
to take people away

00:08:12.630 --> 00:08:13.780
who've been injured.

00:08:13.780 --> 00:08:15.380
This is a thing they do.

00:08:15.380 --> 00:08:17.944
Assuming they don't have a
disability when they start,

00:08:17.944 --> 00:08:19.360
a lot of them do
when they finish.

00:08:21.829 --> 00:08:23.620
Now, you could believe
that you're like me.

00:08:23.620 --> 00:08:26.610
You're invincible and
allergic to nothing.

00:08:26.610 --> 00:08:28.760
But there are other things
that are factors here.

00:08:28.760 --> 00:08:30.850
Lots of people
like to multitask.

00:08:30.850 --> 00:08:33.450
People like to work in
the sun, eat at your desk.

00:08:33.450 --> 00:08:35.450
Sometimes you don't
have headphones handy,

00:08:35.450 --> 00:08:36.409
unless you're at
the airport and they

00:08:36.409 --> 00:08:37.390
have that vending
machine where they

00:08:37.390 --> 00:08:39.047
charge $20 for the headphones.

00:08:39.047 --> 00:08:40.880
And then what are you
going to do with them?

00:08:40.880 --> 00:08:42.370
They don't work half the time.

00:08:42.370 --> 00:08:43.980
I guess that was
just me this morning.

00:08:43.980 --> 00:08:47.240
Also, content isn't always
in your native language.

00:08:47.240 --> 00:08:51.420
So here is somebody trying
to work while eating lunch.

00:08:51.420 --> 00:08:54.090
This describes my day-to-day
activity pretty much.

00:08:54.090 --> 00:08:56.650
Eating at the keyboard
leaves me with one hand free.

00:08:56.650 --> 00:08:58.650
Become very comfortable
using a keyboard instead

00:08:58.650 --> 00:09:00.940
of a mouse in that scenario.

00:09:00.940 --> 00:09:05.420
Somebody working in the sun--
I had to have a cat image,

00:09:05.420 --> 00:09:06.710
so I put it in there.

00:09:06.710 --> 00:09:08.360
So if you've worked
in the sun, you've

00:09:08.360 --> 00:09:10.110
tried to use your
mobile phone in the sun,

00:09:10.110 --> 00:09:13.640
you probably recognize you
can't see the screen very well.

00:09:13.640 --> 00:09:18.060
You need to turn up the contrast
and/or turn up the brightness.

00:09:18.060 --> 00:09:19.650
These guys are
among my favorites

00:09:19.650 --> 00:09:23.950
because they are working in
the sun, they are distracted,

00:09:23.950 --> 00:09:26.542
they are computing
with one hand.

00:09:26.542 --> 00:09:28.750
Frankly, I'm not even
convinced that they're working.

00:09:28.750 --> 00:09:30.890
I think it is quite
likely that they are just

00:09:30.890 --> 00:09:35.450
taking a very long lunch
and calling it a work day.

00:09:35.450 --> 00:09:38.085
I want to be those guys.

00:09:38.085 --> 00:09:39.460
This guy, though,
is my favorite.

00:09:39.460 --> 00:09:42.575
Here's somebody who's working
in a park on the bench, who

00:09:42.575 --> 00:09:45.031
has affixed papers to
himself to block the sun.

00:09:45.031 --> 00:09:47.030
And the best part is, if
you look really closely

00:09:47.030 --> 00:09:50.400
on his lap, that's a typewriter.

00:09:50.400 --> 00:09:53.130
That guy is awesome.

00:09:53.130 --> 00:09:54.920
Maybe Williamsburg
this was taken.

00:09:54.920 --> 00:09:57.610
I don't know.

00:09:57.610 --> 00:10:00.170
Somebody working in a cafe--
he's got a video camera

00:10:00.170 --> 00:10:01.460
on the counter next to him.

00:10:01.460 --> 00:10:03.150
He's got his
headphones plugged in.

00:10:03.150 --> 00:10:05.800
Probably he is doing
some video work.

00:10:05.800 --> 00:10:07.500
And if so, if he's
in a cafe, he's

00:10:07.500 --> 00:10:10.490
not going to be able to hear
the audio from his video,

00:10:10.490 --> 00:10:12.130
and he needs to plug
in his headphones

00:10:12.130 --> 00:10:16.120
in order to do the work
that he's trying to do.

00:10:16.120 --> 00:10:20.330
Somebody in bed with his
significant other, or pet,

00:10:20.330 --> 00:10:22.360
matter of perspective.

00:10:22.360 --> 00:10:25.510
If like me, you've tried
to do any computing in bed,

00:10:25.510 --> 00:10:27.670
you don't want to wake
up the person who's

00:10:27.670 --> 00:10:29.829
with you, because that
doesn't always go well.

00:10:29.829 --> 00:10:32.120
And certainly the ability to
use headphones and control

00:10:32.120 --> 00:10:36.060
brightness is very
important in that scenario.

00:10:36.060 --> 00:10:38.650
This image is analogous
to where I live.

00:10:38.650 --> 00:10:40.330
I don't live in
these apartments.

00:10:40.330 --> 00:10:42.530
I live in a house, but on
either side of my house

00:10:42.530 --> 00:10:44.240
is a motorcycle.

00:10:44.240 --> 00:10:46.570
And one side is a
guy with a Harley,

00:10:46.570 --> 00:10:48.770
and the other side is
a guy with a Honda,

00:10:48.770 --> 00:10:52.350
and they like to see who can
out-motorcycle each other.

00:10:52.350 --> 00:10:54.410
They like to rev their
engines, and their engines

00:10:54.410 --> 00:10:57.240
are always revving right during
a critical moment in whatever

00:10:57.240 --> 00:11:01.010
show I'm watching or
conversation or whatever.

00:11:01.010 --> 00:11:03.130
So sometimes the
environmental factors

00:11:03.130 --> 00:11:07.270
are outside your control,
even when you're at home.

00:11:07.270 --> 00:11:09.990
This young woman is
in another country,

00:11:09.990 --> 00:11:11.115
doesn't speak the language.

00:11:11.115 --> 00:11:14.330
She's trying to find information
about how to get home.

00:11:14.330 --> 00:11:16.962
The keyboard is probably not
in her native language, either,

00:11:16.962 --> 00:11:18.420
which means the
keys are different.

00:11:18.420 --> 00:11:19.470
The screen is different.

00:11:19.470 --> 00:11:20.636
She's just not used to this.

00:11:20.636 --> 00:11:23.170
She's a completely
competent computer user,

00:11:23.170 --> 00:11:25.160
but when you're
in a foreign land,

00:11:25.160 --> 00:11:28.920
things just aren't
quite so easy to use.

00:11:28.920 --> 00:11:32.300
Tech support is another
factor to consider.

00:11:32.300 --> 00:11:34.580
If like me, every time you
go to your parents' house

00:11:34.580 --> 00:11:36.580
for Thanksgiving, the
first thing you have to do

00:11:36.580 --> 00:11:39.820
is get the printer working
again, fix the browser,

00:11:39.820 --> 00:11:43.676
uninstall some malware,
and all those other things,

00:11:43.676 --> 00:11:45.800
that's a lot of time that
you spend on your holiday

00:11:45.800 --> 00:11:48.130
when you could be eating
turkey and pie that you are

00:11:48.130 --> 00:11:50.572
busy trying to help
get your parents up

00:11:50.572 --> 00:11:52.780
and running again so that
they don't have to call you

00:11:52.780 --> 00:11:55.841
during the week in
the office to ask you

00:11:55.841 --> 00:11:58.215
what that big purple box is
in the corner of your browser

00:11:58.215 --> 00:12:02.030
that's blocking 800 trackers.

00:12:02.030 --> 00:12:06.090
So the general message here is
that supporting accessibility

00:12:06.090 --> 00:12:10.210
now, today, is going
to help future you.

00:12:10.210 --> 00:12:12.950
Because you're all
going to get older.

00:12:12.950 --> 00:12:14.630
You're all going to get older.

00:12:14.630 --> 00:12:17.070
Am I breaking the
fourth wall there?

00:12:17.070 --> 00:12:17.990
OK.

00:12:17.990 --> 00:12:19.260
Nobody's laughing.

00:12:19.260 --> 00:12:20.840
Laugh.

00:12:20.840 --> 00:12:24.480
So it's going to help
serve future you.

00:12:24.480 --> 00:12:26.840
Supporting accessibility
now also helps

00:12:26.840 --> 00:12:30.114
the injured version of you and
the encumbered version of you.

00:12:30.114 --> 00:12:31.280
You don't have to be broken.

00:12:31.280 --> 00:12:34.750
You could just be working
in the sun or on the train

00:12:34.750 --> 00:12:35.790
or on a staircase.

00:12:35.790 --> 00:12:38.630
I don't know why you would be.

00:12:38.630 --> 00:12:41.920
If you get younger developers
to buy into this now,

00:12:41.920 --> 00:12:44.960
it's helping future you.

00:12:44.960 --> 00:12:47.530
Get that next generation
of developers to say,

00:12:47.530 --> 00:12:49.430
yup, we see what
you're talking about.

00:12:49.430 --> 00:12:50.550
Let's make that happen.

00:12:50.550 --> 00:12:52.930
And as you age, and
ostensibly as you move away

00:12:52.930 --> 00:12:54.860
from doing day-to-day
development

00:12:54.860 --> 00:12:58.260
or being able to be involved in
software the same way you maybe

00:12:58.260 --> 00:13:01.520
are now, you'll have a
whole generation behind you

00:13:01.520 --> 00:13:06.320
who can make sure that you can
still do the things you do.

00:13:06.320 --> 00:13:10.220
So accessibility is often
regarded as a checklist.

00:13:10.220 --> 00:13:12.660
There are the Web Content
Accessibility Guidelines.

00:13:12.660 --> 00:13:14.570
There are internal checklists.

00:13:14.570 --> 00:13:17.630
There are different standards
that talk about the things that

00:13:17.630 --> 00:13:18.630
you should or shouldn't.

00:13:18.630 --> 00:13:21.214
Do but accessibility
is not a checklist.

00:13:21.214 --> 00:13:22.630
It's a good place
to start, but it

00:13:22.630 --> 00:13:24.810
doesn't get you to the finish.

00:13:24.810 --> 00:13:27.610
This example I think is a
beautiful example of somebody

00:13:27.610 --> 00:13:31.260
who has satisfied all
the checks on a list.

00:13:31.260 --> 00:13:32.700
They had a set of stairs.

00:13:32.700 --> 00:13:33.990
They needed to have a ramp.

00:13:33.990 --> 00:13:35.430
They probably had limited space.

00:13:35.430 --> 00:13:37.640
They still needed
to have hand rails.

00:13:37.640 --> 00:13:40.270
They satisfied everything
on the checklist.

00:13:40.270 --> 00:13:42.500
The problem with
these stairs, though,

00:13:42.500 --> 00:13:48.317
is if you aren't using a
wheelchair, step, step, trip,

00:13:48.317 --> 00:13:50.650
stumble, stumble, step, step,
step, step, trip, stumble,

00:13:50.650 --> 00:13:52.420
stumble, step, step.

00:13:52.420 --> 00:13:55.640
If you're using these
stairs just as stairs,

00:13:55.640 --> 00:13:57.770
that ramp cuts through
at an awkward angle,

00:13:57.770 --> 00:14:01.100
and people are always
tripping on them, OK?

00:14:01.100 --> 00:14:03.870
If you're using these
stairs in a wheelchair,

00:14:03.870 --> 00:14:05.131
the angles are all wrong.

00:14:05.131 --> 00:14:07.130
Not only do you have to
make a really tight turn

00:14:07.130 --> 00:14:11.460
at each platform, but
the slope is too great.

00:14:11.460 --> 00:14:14.500
The average wheelchair user
can't navigate that easily.

00:14:14.500 --> 00:14:17.790
So those turns that you see,
each little platform, ends

00:14:17.790 --> 00:14:20.100
in a stone wall, except
for the last one, where

00:14:20.100 --> 00:14:23.240
it ends in a hilarious
staircase fall in case

00:14:23.240 --> 00:14:24.900
you get going too fast.

00:14:24.900 --> 00:14:26.020
That's unusable.

00:14:26.020 --> 00:14:28.721
It's actually dangerous for
somebody in a wheelchair.

00:14:28.721 --> 00:14:30.470
And it's moderately
dangerous for somebody

00:14:30.470 --> 00:14:32.060
who's not in a wheelchair.

00:14:32.060 --> 00:14:33.890
But they satisfied a checklist.

00:14:33.890 --> 00:14:34.840
So good for them.

00:14:34.840 --> 00:14:35.970
They did that.

00:14:35.970 --> 00:14:38.260
Accessibility is
an ongoing process.

00:14:38.260 --> 00:14:40.660
You can't just do the
checklist and call it done.

00:14:40.660 --> 00:14:43.170
You need to pay attention
that things change.

00:14:43.170 --> 00:14:44.370
Situations change.

00:14:44.370 --> 00:14:45.740
Technologies change.

00:14:45.740 --> 00:14:49.230
Assistive technology changes.

00:14:49.230 --> 00:14:53.150
This is a drugstore that did
a great job putting a ramp in.

00:14:53.150 --> 00:14:56.685
But what they failed to
do is clear the snow off.

00:14:56.685 --> 00:14:58.060
And when they did
that, then they

00:14:58.060 --> 00:15:00.980
put potted plants on the ramp.

00:15:00.980 --> 00:15:04.217
So yeah, we put the ramp up
there, and we did it right,

00:15:04.217 --> 00:15:06.300
and the angles are right
and everything's perfect.

00:15:06.300 --> 00:15:07.820
But now that winter
has come, we've

00:15:07.820 --> 00:15:11.680
made it completely unusable--
completely unusable.

00:15:11.680 --> 00:15:14.540
So this is an ongoing process.

00:15:14.540 --> 00:15:18.199
This is something that you have
to constantly stay on top of.

00:15:18.199 --> 00:15:19.990
So I'm going to talk
about some techniques.

00:15:19.990 --> 00:15:22.120
Some of you might have
worked with user stories.

00:15:22.120 --> 00:15:24.950
Has anybody in the room worked
with user stories before?

00:15:24.950 --> 00:15:26.100
OK, good.

00:15:26.100 --> 00:15:29.360
I'll spend a little bit of
time on this, not too much.

00:15:29.360 --> 00:15:31.715
If you're unfamiliar with
them, the idea of a user story

00:15:31.715 --> 00:15:35.250
is you talk about a user, the
outcome that that user wants,

00:15:35.250 --> 00:15:36.780
and the value of that outcome.

00:15:36.780 --> 00:15:38.820
When you're writing
them out, As user,

00:15:38.820 --> 00:15:41.610
I want outcome so that value.

00:15:41.610 --> 00:15:44.550
There are some variations
on how you write that.

00:15:44.550 --> 00:15:47.350
So I have some
selfish user stories.

00:15:47.350 --> 00:15:49.420
As a user, I was
on a sunlit patio.

00:15:49.420 --> 00:15:52.990
I want to be able to read the
content and see the controls.

00:15:52.990 --> 00:15:54.520
Maybe I'm looking something up.

00:15:54.520 --> 00:15:56.740
Maybe I'm actually doing my job.

00:15:56.740 --> 00:16:01.260
If the sun's shining, I still
want to be able to do my job.

00:16:01.260 --> 00:16:04.430
As a user in bed with
a sleeping spouse,

00:16:04.430 --> 00:16:06.860
I want to watch a training
video in silence so that I

00:16:06.860 --> 00:16:08.820
can get caught up at work.

00:16:08.820 --> 00:16:11.650
I'm sure many of us have spent
some time trying to get caught

00:16:11.650 --> 00:16:13.260
up at work on our own time.

00:16:13.260 --> 00:16:15.010
And in bed is kind of
a nice way to do it.

00:16:15.010 --> 00:16:17.150
That way if you fall asleep,
you're already there.

00:16:17.150 --> 00:16:21.000
It's easy, other than
drooling on the keyboard.

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:24.370
In order to click links, as a
user was no elbow room in coach

00:16:24.370 --> 00:16:26.610
class with the tiny
track pad, I want

00:16:26.610 --> 00:16:31.010
click areas to be large
enough and adequately spaced.

00:16:31.010 --> 00:16:33.460
I'm sure all of you
have been on a flight.

00:16:33.460 --> 00:16:35.140
I'm sure some of you
have tried to use

00:16:35.140 --> 00:16:36.410
your computer on a flight.

00:16:36.410 --> 00:16:38.290
And you know your
elbows have to stick

00:16:38.290 --> 00:16:40.440
to your pelvis to do anything.

00:16:40.440 --> 00:16:42.900
And suddenly you have
a mobility impairment.

00:16:42.900 --> 00:16:47.610
It becomes very difficult
to mouse around on a page.

00:16:47.610 --> 00:16:49.740
As a user distracted
by the TV, I

00:16:49.740 --> 00:16:54.210
want clear headings and labels
so that I don't lose my place.

00:16:54.210 --> 00:16:57.710
I like to watch television
while I'm filling out tax forms.

00:16:57.710 --> 00:16:58.720
Call me crazy.

00:16:58.720 --> 00:17:00.410
And I want to know
what my progress is.

00:17:00.410 --> 00:17:01.760
I want to know what
those fields are.

00:17:01.760 --> 00:17:03.468
Sometimes when it's
a placeholder instead

00:17:03.468 --> 00:17:05.599
of a label on the field,
once I type in there

00:17:05.599 --> 00:17:07.079
I have no idea what
I just entered,

00:17:07.079 --> 00:17:09.079
and I have to go back and
delete and start over.

00:17:11.630 --> 00:17:15.510
So I've broken them down
for some different types

00:17:15.510 --> 00:17:18.849
of disabilities for
physical impairments.

00:17:18.849 --> 00:17:20.510
As a keyboard-only
user, I want to be

00:17:20.510 --> 00:17:22.569
able to use the
entire application.

00:17:22.569 --> 00:17:24.819
I want to navigate a product
list with the Tab key

00:17:24.819 --> 00:17:27.099
so I can find the right option.

00:17:27.099 --> 00:17:29.510
In order to click links as
a limited-mobility user,

00:17:29.510 --> 00:17:32.700
I want click areas to be large
enough and adequately spaced.

00:17:32.700 --> 00:17:35.430
Because when you hit the wrong
one and you have to go back,

00:17:35.430 --> 00:17:36.820
that's time.

00:17:36.820 --> 00:17:39.390
That's time and frustration.

00:17:39.390 --> 00:17:42.020
Visual impairment--
as a color blind user,

00:17:42.020 --> 00:17:46.320
I want to be able to see the
links in the page content.

00:17:46.320 --> 00:17:48.480
As a low vision user,
I want to zoom the page

00:17:48.480 --> 00:17:51.120
so that I can read the content.

00:17:51.120 --> 00:17:53.060
In order to use the
site as a blind user,

00:17:53.060 --> 00:17:55.810
I want to use a screen
reader to navigate.

00:17:55.810 --> 00:17:59.140
That's a form of
assistive technology.

00:17:59.140 --> 00:18:02.460
Hearing impairment--
as a low hearing user,

00:18:02.460 --> 00:18:05.570
I want to be able to
access transcripts.

00:18:05.570 --> 00:18:07.700
I want access to
closed captions so

00:18:07.700 --> 00:18:10.930
that I can use training videos
or just watch the Star Wars

00:18:10.930 --> 00:18:11.430
trailer.

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:15.220
It's a timely reference.

00:18:15.220 --> 00:18:16.342
OK.

00:18:16.342 --> 00:18:18.580
It's timely.

00:18:18.580 --> 00:18:21.090
In order to participate in
a webinar as a deaf user,

00:18:21.090 --> 00:18:23.510
I wanted real-time
captioning or transcripts.

00:18:23.510 --> 00:18:26.070
This is really key
at conferences,

00:18:26.070 --> 00:18:28.230
and some of the better
conferences are doing that.

00:18:28.230 --> 00:18:29.890
While the speaker is
up there, somebody

00:18:29.890 --> 00:18:33.420
is live transcribing
it, and it's awesome.

00:18:33.420 --> 00:18:36.130
And you also see how often
you say the word "um."

00:18:36.130 --> 00:18:38.950
So it's a little bit humbling.

00:18:38.950 --> 00:18:43.930
Cognitive impairment-- as a user
with a vestibular disorder--

00:18:43.930 --> 00:18:47.930
that is an off-kilter
balance, essentially-- I

00:18:47.930 --> 00:18:51.290
want to be able to disable
parallax scrolling,

00:18:51.290 --> 00:18:56.920
because that can cause
disorientation and nausea.

00:18:56.920 --> 00:18:59.210
As a user with
dyscalculia-- that's

00:18:59.210 --> 00:19:02.950
the number transposition-- I
want distinct number fields

00:19:02.950 --> 00:19:04.950
for each block of digits
in a credit card number

00:19:04.950 --> 00:19:07.120
so that I can
purchase a product.

00:19:07.120 --> 00:19:09.860
One long field where you
enter all 12 to 16 digits

00:19:09.860 --> 00:19:11.880
can be very confusing.

00:19:11.880 --> 00:19:14.950
Breaking them up can be useful.

00:19:14.950 --> 00:19:18.290
In order to not get confused on
pages with long text passages,

00:19:18.290 --> 00:19:21.610
as a user with dyslexia I
want control over text size,

00:19:21.610 --> 00:19:24.520
spacing, and/or
alignment, essentially

00:19:24.520 --> 00:19:27.880
allowing me to shape the content
to a way that's easy for me

00:19:27.880 --> 00:19:28.380
to read.

00:19:31.890 --> 00:19:34.370
I was tempted to put
personas in here,

00:19:34.370 --> 00:19:37.070
but Sarah Horton and
Whitney Quesenbery

00:19:37.070 --> 00:19:41.820
have done a great job on putting
together personas already.

00:19:41.820 --> 00:19:45.840
And you should go steal them,
because they're pre-written,

00:19:45.840 --> 00:19:47.640
and they're good to go.

00:19:47.640 --> 00:19:49.974
One thing I would
like to note, though,

00:19:49.974 --> 00:19:52.390
having worked with personas
before, I know from experience

00:19:52.390 --> 00:19:55.750
that personas are sometimes the
first thing that will get cut.

00:19:55.750 --> 00:19:57.710
You want to get
down to n personas,

00:19:57.710 --> 00:20:00.020
often that number is
maybe four or five.

00:20:00.020 --> 00:20:02.222
And once you start
folding in personas

00:20:02.222 --> 00:20:04.180
that are dedicated to
people with disabilities,

00:20:04.180 --> 00:20:06.950
those are often the
first ones to get cut.

00:20:06.950 --> 00:20:12.230
So what I do is I fold
in some variations.

00:20:12.230 --> 00:20:15.460
I take a regular persona,
and I add some things to it

00:20:15.460 --> 00:20:20.260
from these selfish
approaches that help.

00:20:20.260 --> 00:20:23.550
So if I'm a persona, I work
when I should be relaxing,

00:20:23.550 --> 00:20:25.270
and I relax when I
should be working.

00:20:25.270 --> 00:20:28.270
I have a reverse day, because
I'm weird, or I'm a slacker.

00:20:28.270 --> 00:20:29.840
I'm not sure which.

00:20:29.840 --> 00:20:31.450
I live between
motorcycles, which

00:20:31.450 --> 00:20:34.140
means I've always
got audio issues,

00:20:34.140 --> 00:20:36.400
always got a hearing impairment.

00:20:36.400 --> 00:20:39.910
I work late at night with the
TV on, so I'm always distracted.

00:20:39.910 --> 00:20:41.680
I use the subtitles in Netflix.

00:20:41.680 --> 00:20:43.720
I'm always relying on
the closed captioning.

00:20:43.720 --> 00:20:46.090
I'm heavily reliant on that.

00:20:46.090 --> 00:20:48.740
I also keep all screens
as dark as possible,

00:20:48.740 --> 00:20:50.844
partly because I want
to save my battery,

00:20:50.844 --> 00:20:53.010
and partly because I don't
want to scorch my retinas

00:20:53.010 --> 00:20:54.680
in the middle of the night.

00:20:54.680 --> 00:20:57.340
So these are all
scenarios where you

00:20:57.340 --> 00:21:00.230
can fold these into a persona.

00:21:00.230 --> 00:21:05.710
And just as I had run through
some sample user stories,

00:21:05.710 --> 00:21:09.950
you can quietly fold these in
without necessarily giving up

00:21:09.950 --> 00:21:11.830
that that's what
you're trying to do.

00:21:11.830 --> 00:21:14.250
You can sneak them in.

00:21:14.250 --> 00:21:16.260
So this one is one
of my favorites,

00:21:16.260 --> 00:21:20.290
the click links as a user with
no elbow room in coach class.

00:21:20.290 --> 00:21:22.570
People are going to say this
is important for the CEO.

00:21:22.570 --> 00:21:23.880
We need the CEO
to like this piece

00:21:23.880 --> 00:21:25.139
of software, this application.

00:21:25.139 --> 00:21:26.680
Then you start to
ask some questions.

00:21:26.680 --> 00:21:30.660
Does the CEO work on the train
or on a plane or in a boat

00:21:30.660 --> 00:21:31.950
by a moat?

00:21:31.950 --> 00:21:33.780
These are all factors
that you can use

00:21:33.780 --> 00:21:35.160
to fold into your user stories.

00:21:35.160 --> 00:21:38.270
Listen, this is something
that he'll encounter.

00:21:38.270 --> 00:21:39.750
We're now supporting the CEO.

00:21:39.750 --> 00:21:42.060
We are now doing that
thing that you want.

00:21:42.060 --> 00:21:44.012
We're making it work for him.

00:21:44.012 --> 00:21:45.720
Nobody needs to know
that you're actually

00:21:45.720 --> 00:21:48.920
sneaking in some
accessibility best practices,

00:21:48.920 --> 00:21:52.550
just like nobody needs to know
is that they map to real user

00:21:52.550 --> 00:21:56.070
stories or that you're
folding some of these ideas

00:21:56.070 --> 00:22:00.580
into personas that otherwise
might be completely discarded.

00:22:00.580 --> 00:22:02.670
So you can sort
of stealthily fold

00:22:02.670 --> 00:22:04.300
some of this stuff
in there, and people

00:22:04.300 --> 00:22:06.645
don't need to know about it.

00:22:06.645 --> 00:22:09.570
We're going to run
through some basic tests.

00:22:09.570 --> 00:22:11.600
These are tests
that anybody can do.

00:22:11.600 --> 00:22:16.540
If you have a web browser,
you can do the tests.

00:22:16.540 --> 00:22:19.390
It's really that simple.

00:22:19.390 --> 00:22:21.300
Click on the field labels.

00:22:21.300 --> 00:22:23.190
When you're on a form,
it's the quickest way

00:22:23.190 --> 00:22:26.640
to see if the field label
is associated with the form

00:22:26.640 --> 00:22:27.510
control.

00:22:27.510 --> 00:22:30.389
Usually it's the label element.

00:22:30.389 --> 00:22:32.430
So when you click it, does
the field get focused?

00:22:32.430 --> 00:22:35.870
Does the radio button or
checkbox get selected?

00:22:35.870 --> 00:22:38.810
So in this example from
Buffalo Soccer Club,

00:22:38.810 --> 00:22:40.389
an inner-city youth
soccer program

00:22:40.389 --> 00:22:42.180
we started up at
Algonquin a few years ago,

00:22:42.180 --> 00:22:45.569
and which we're very proud
of and which you are now

00:22:45.569 --> 00:22:47.360
going to see as my
example throughout these

00:22:47.360 --> 00:22:49.960
slides because it's awesome.

00:22:49.960 --> 00:22:52.610
The contact form, if I
click on Name-- boom--

00:22:52.610 --> 00:22:55.840
it puts focus in that
field, ready to go.

00:22:55.840 --> 00:22:57.890
That means that those two
fields are correlated.

00:22:57.890 --> 00:22:59.598
That means that
assistive technology will

00:22:59.598 --> 00:23:01.790
be able to draw a
connection between them,

00:23:01.790 --> 00:23:05.110
and the user will know
specifically what field

00:23:05.110 --> 00:23:07.660
he or she is filling out.

00:23:07.660 --> 00:23:09.590
Unplug your mouse.

00:23:09.590 --> 00:23:13.680
My variation on this is to
unplug somebody else's mouse.

00:23:13.680 --> 00:23:15.850
Because that's hilarious,
unless it's your boss.

00:23:15.850 --> 00:23:17.290
Then it's not
quite so hilarious.

00:23:17.290 --> 00:23:20.000
And then you have to
apologize, return it.

00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:21.330
So turn off the track pad.

00:23:21.330 --> 00:23:23.900
Turn off all those
pointing devices.

00:23:23.900 --> 00:23:27.240
And see if you can still
use the entire application,

00:23:27.240 --> 00:23:29.710
if you can use the entire page.

00:23:29.710 --> 00:23:31.157
Can you tell which
item has focus

00:23:31.157 --> 00:23:32.240
if you're tabbing through?

00:23:32.240 --> 00:23:35.340
Do you know at a glance
where is the cursor,

00:23:35.340 --> 00:23:36.800
where is it right now?

00:23:36.800 --> 00:23:38.300
And does it match
your expectations?

00:23:38.300 --> 00:23:40.240
If you start to tab
through the page

00:23:40.240 --> 00:23:43.710
and it goes, field
1, field 2, field 14,

00:23:43.710 --> 00:23:45.200
you've got a bit of a problem.

00:23:45.200 --> 00:23:48.910
And you'll need to take a
