00:29:29.910 --> 00:29:32.080
and audio descriptions.

00:29:32.080 --> 00:29:33.590
You can watch the entire movie.

00:29:33.590 --> 00:29:34.180
It's great.

00:29:34.180 --> 00:29:36.010
And I think it's
in Spanish as well.

00:29:36.010 --> 00:29:37.760
So watch it, and you'll
get a good example

00:29:37.760 --> 00:29:41.830
of how these can be effective
and how they can be useful.

00:29:41.830 --> 00:29:44.345
And for giggles, just
put mute on your computer

00:29:44.345 --> 00:29:47.430
or your headphones.

00:29:47.430 --> 00:29:50.140
Hyperlinks-- hyperlinks
are sort of the thing that

00:29:50.140 --> 00:29:52.650
make the web what the web is.

00:29:52.650 --> 00:29:55.260
If you have a click
here, more, link to,

00:29:55.260 --> 00:29:56.300
consider changing those.

00:29:56.300 --> 00:29:57.924
Let those be descriptive,
what the user

00:29:57.924 --> 00:30:00.540
is going to actually
end up going to visit.

00:30:00.540 --> 00:30:02.470
Assistive technology
allows you to navigate

00:30:02.470 --> 00:30:03.480
through all the links,
and they're just

00:30:03.480 --> 00:30:06.021
going to hear click here, click
here, click here, click here,

00:30:06.021 --> 00:30:09.030
click here, click
here-- not very useful.

00:30:09.030 --> 00:30:13.060
If you're using all caps
or a full URL or emoticons,

00:30:13.060 --> 00:30:15.270
remember that might
be pronounced in a way

00:30:15.270 --> 00:30:18.320
that you don't expect, maybe
spelled out letter by letter.

00:30:18.320 --> 00:30:21.190
A URL spelled out letter by
letter is painful to listen to,

00:30:21.190 --> 00:30:22.090
by the way.

00:30:22.090 --> 00:30:23.500
I recommend you try it sometime.

00:30:23.500 --> 00:30:26.010
It's awful.

00:30:26.010 --> 00:30:28.700
Are you warning the user
before opening new windows?

00:30:28.700 --> 00:30:30.860
This is critical
for managing focus

00:30:30.860 --> 00:30:35.600
for users who are using either
assistive technology or not,

00:30:35.600 --> 00:30:38.510
who just have trouble managing
the multiple interfaces.

00:30:38.510 --> 00:30:41.610
At least give them a heads-up
that's going to happen.

00:30:41.610 --> 00:30:43.833
Do links to downloads
provide helpful info?

00:30:43.833 --> 00:30:47.664
Are you telling them this
is a PDF and it's 35 meg?

00:30:47.664 --> 00:30:49.330
They can choose to
download it, but it's

00:30:49.330 --> 00:30:51.430
better than surprising them.

00:30:51.430 --> 00:30:53.620
Are you using pagination links?

00:30:53.620 --> 00:30:57.910
If it's a blog, for example,
can they jump ahead a few pages?

00:30:57.910 --> 00:30:59.050
Can they jump back?

00:30:59.050 --> 00:31:02.000
Is this something they
have the freedom to do?

00:31:02.000 --> 00:31:03.590
Are your links obvious?

00:31:03.590 --> 00:31:06.250
I always recommend
underlining them.

00:31:06.250 --> 00:31:08.290
But make sure that
they're are obvious.

00:31:08.290 --> 00:31:11.400
Make sure that there is alt
text for any image links.

00:31:11.400 --> 00:31:14.020
Just because the image means
one thing in one context,

00:31:14.020 --> 00:31:16.250
if you make it a
link, it probably

00:31:16.250 --> 00:31:20.410
should have its alt text
updated to reflect that.

00:31:20.410 --> 00:31:22.430
And is the link text consistent?

00:31:22.430 --> 00:31:26.711
If you're pointing to the same
35-megabyte PDF annual report,

00:31:26.711 --> 00:31:28.210
maybe every time
you link to it, you

00:31:28.210 --> 00:31:31.066
should say Annual
Report 35 meg PDF.

00:31:31.066 --> 00:31:32.440
That way they
don't think they're

00:31:32.440 --> 00:31:34.106
getting a different
document every time,

00:31:34.106 --> 00:31:38.300
and they're not downloading
it over and over and over.

00:31:38.300 --> 00:31:39.550
How much time do I have again?

