00:31:57.300 --> 00:31:59.650
The nice thing is this
is the last section.

00:31:59.650 --> 00:32:02.620
So that's awesome.

00:32:02.620 --> 00:32:07.160
If you don't know what ARIA is,
Web Accessibility Initiative--

00:32:07.160 --> 00:32:10.320
Accessible Rich
Internet Applications.

00:32:10.320 --> 00:32:14.500
ARIA adds accessibility
information to HTML elements

00:32:14.500 --> 00:32:17.449
and to elements that
aren't necessarily HTML.

00:32:17.449 --> 00:32:19.240
It can be sued with
prior versions of HTML.

00:32:19.240 --> 00:32:23.480
So if you, like me, are rocking
some HTML 3.2 page somewhere,

00:32:23.480 --> 00:32:24.470
go nuts.

00:32:24.470 --> 00:32:26.120
Just be prepared to
throw some ARIA on

00:32:26.120 --> 00:32:27.960
there so that it can
be useful for people

00:32:27.960 --> 00:32:30.130
with assistive technology.

00:32:30.130 --> 00:32:34.970
The 1.0 specification was
published in March of 2014,

00:32:34.970 --> 00:32:38.120
but it had been in use and
been supported for a long time

00:32:38.120 --> 00:32:39.010
before that.

00:32:39.010 --> 00:32:41.320
So this technology
has got great support

00:32:41.320 --> 00:32:43.690
and has been out
there for a while.

00:32:43.690 --> 00:32:45.850
There are five
rules of using ARIA.

00:32:45.850 --> 00:32:48.360
They're pretty straightforward,
which is awesome.

00:32:48.360 --> 00:32:49.960
And they're simple.

00:32:49.960 --> 00:32:53.090
The first is if you can use
a native HTML5 element that

00:32:53.090 --> 00:32:58.810
has the semantics or behavior
that you want built in, do it.

00:32:58.810 --> 00:33:00.460
Just use it.

00:33:00.460 --> 00:33:00.960
Good to go.

00:33:00.960 --> 00:33:02.334
You don't need to
worry about it.

00:33:02.334 --> 00:33:03.070
You want an h1?

00:33:03.070 --> 00:33:03.820
Great.

00:33:03.820 --> 00:33:05.260
You want a header tag?

00:33:05.260 --> 00:33:05.760
Great.

00:33:05.760 --> 00:33:07.150
A footer tag?

00:33:07.150 --> 00:33:07.850
Awesome.

00:33:07.850 --> 00:33:08.980
You're off to the races.

00:33:08.980 --> 00:33:10.480
You probably don't
need to use ARIA.

00:33:10.480 --> 00:33:13.200
You're doing a good job with it.

00:33:13.200 --> 00:33:15.240
Do not change native semantics.

00:33:15.240 --> 00:33:18.290
That h1, if you want
people to click on it,

00:33:18.290 --> 00:33:20.720
don't put a role
of "button" on it.

00:33:20.720 --> 00:33:23.610
Once you start changing
those semantics,

00:33:23.610 --> 00:33:27.700
assistive technology doesn't
know what to do in every case.

00:33:27.700 --> 00:33:31.110
It's not going to bind
that to keys, for example.

00:33:31.110 --> 00:33:32.700
Leave your h1 as
an one as an h1.

00:33:32.700 --> 00:33:36.330
Put a button in there if
you really want a button.

00:33:36.330 --> 00:33:38.390
All interactive
ARIA controls must

00:33:38.390 --> 00:33:41.110
be usable with the keyboard.

00:33:41.110 --> 00:33:43.590
So if you want
somebody to click,

00:33:43.590 --> 00:33:46.290
let them also use the Tab
key to get to it and Space

00:33:46.290 --> 00:33:48.270
or Enter an order
to activate it.

00:33:48.270 --> 00:33:49.930
If there's a drag
and drop, you need

00:33:49.930 --> 00:33:54.670
to figure out a way to make that
work with the keyboard only.

00:33:54.670 --> 00:33:57.960
Do not use role "presentation"
or ARIA-hidden "true"

00:33:57.960 --> 00:33:59.880
on any element that gets focus.

00:33:59.880 --> 00:34:02.670
By focus, I mean
tabbing through the page

00:34:02.670 --> 00:34:04.940
until it gets that
outline, that caret.

00:34:04.940 --> 00:34:09.330
If you do that, users
won't be able to focus it.

00:34:09.330 --> 00:34:10.870
I can't tab to
that element once I

00:34:10.870 --> 00:34:14.699
put hidden "true" or ARIA-hidden
"true" or role "presentation."

00:34:14.699 --> 00:34:19.060
It just isn't available
in my tabbing order.

00:34:19.060 --> 00:34:22.435
All interactive elements
must have an accessible name.

00:34:22.435 --> 00:34:24.060
Typically if you have
a button element,

00:34:24.060 --> 00:34:26.000
it's the text inside the button.

00:34:26.000 --> 00:34:28.900
That's pretty easy to do.

00:34:28.900 --> 00:34:31.100
Alt text on an
image, for example,

00:34:31.100 --> 00:34:32.690
that is the accessible name.

00:34:32.690 --> 00:34:34.230
There is a relatively
complex way

00:34:34.230 --> 00:34:36.469
of doing the accessible
name calculation.

00:34:36.469 --> 00:34:38.760
I'm not going to stress you
out with that, because it's

00:34:38.760 --> 00:34:40.830
very easy to just fire
up some technology

00:34:40.830 --> 00:34:43.030
and check to see what
it's speaking to you,

00:34:43.030 --> 00:34:46.719
and then you'll know if
you're doing the right one.

00:34:46.719 --> 00:34:51.590
So here's an example of
something not to do with ARIA.

00:34:51.590 --> 00:34:53.989
So some people like to
take divs and make them

00:34:53.989 --> 00:34:55.800
into buttons or links.

00:34:55.800 --> 00:34:59.572
So they put an onclick
handler on a div.

00:34:59.572 --> 00:35:01.280
Well, they do that,
and then they quickly

00:35:01.280 --> 00:35:03.970
find out that, well, they
can't use it with the keyboard.

00:35:03.970 --> 00:35:06.040
So they add a tab
index of zero to it.

00:35:06.040 --> 00:35:09.380
OK, now I can at least get
there with the keyboard.

00:35:09.380 --> 00:35:11.470
But when I hit the Enter
key, nothing happens.

00:35:11.470 --> 00:35:13.940
So I have to put an onkeypress.

00:35:13.940 --> 00:35:16.190
OK, so I put the onclick.

00:35:16.190 --> 00:35:17.140
I put the onkey press.

00:35:17.140 --> 00:35:19.050
I can tab to it.

00:35:19.050 --> 00:35:21.830
By the way, I'm excluding the
key codes and other things.

00:35:21.830 --> 00:35:23.320
I'm keeping this short.

00:35:23.320 --> 00:35:25.340
Key codes are at the
bottom if you really

00:35:25.340 --> 00:35:28.090
want to check my math.

00:35:28.090 --> 00:35:31.050
But the thing is still
not completely useful,

00:35:31.050 --> 00:35:33.220
because it doesn't get
the native features

00:35:33.220 --> 00:35:34.480
from the browser.

00:35:34.480 --> 00:35:36.730
So now you put a
role "button" on it.

00:35:36.730 --> 00:35:39.430
So now you can do all
the things with this div

00:35:39.430 --> 00:35:42.650
that you could do with
the button element.

00:35:42.650 --> 00:35:45.507
Or you could use a button.

00:35:45.507 --> 00:35:46.590
I mean, it is that simple.

00:35:46.590 --> 00:35:48.320
The element already exists.

00:35:48.320 --> 00:35:51.010
In most cases when you're
trying to repurpose an element,

00:35:51.010 --> 00:35:53.290
there's already an element
that will do it for you.

00:35:53.290 --> 00:35:55.710
There's already some ARIA
that will help you there.

00:35:55.710 --> 00:35:57.310
This is just standard HTML.

00:35:57.310 --> 00:35:58.370
There's no ARIA in there.

00:35:58.370 --> 00:36:00.160
And that's probably
the best use of ARIA

00:36:00.160 --> 00:36:03.950
is not using it because
you don't need it.

00:36:03.950 --> 00:36:06.300
There are some things to note.

00:36:06.300 --> 00:36:08.700
ARIA can be overused.

00:36:08.700 --> 00:36:10.790
There are cases where
people have said, oh, well,

00:36:10.790 --> 00:36:11.289
don't worry.

00:36:11.289 --> 00:36:14.090
We'll just sprinkle some
ARIA on it, and it will work.

00:36:14.090 --> 00:36:17.215
And I link to two articles,
one by Jared Smith from WebAIM,

00:36:17.215 --> 00:36:19.910
"Accessibility Lipstick
on a Usability Pig."

00:36:19.910 --> 00:36:21.250
It's a great read.

00:36:21.250 --> 00:36:24.320
Marco Zehe also has "What
is WAI-ARIA, what does

00:36:24.320 --> 00:36:25.810
it do for me, and whatnot?"

00:36:25.810 --> 00:36:28.150
And those are both
cautionary tales

00:36:28.150 --> 00:36:30.370
of how you can
overuse it and create

00:36:30.370 --> 00:36:34.960
very much the opposite
effect that you're going for.

00:36:34.960 --> 00:36:37.870
HTML5 has these
beautiful elements

00:36:37.870 --> 00:36:40.640
built in that have
accessibility already

00:36:40.640 --> 00:36:43.740
there built into it by default.
It's just what it does.

00:36:43.740 --> 00:36:47.120
Header, nav, main, use
one per page, please.

00:36:47.120 --> 00:36:50.352
A side footer, form,
it's already there.

00:36:50.352 --> 00:36:51.560
The browser knows what to do.

00:36:51.560 --> 00:36:53.580
It can through these landmarks.

00:36:53.580 --> 00:36:56.020
It can navigate into
different sections of them.

00:36:56.020 --> 00:36:58.810
They map to ARIA
landmark roles already.

00:36:58.810 --> 00:37:00.470
Header has a role of "banner."

00:37:00.470 --> 00:37:03.419
Main has a role of "main."

00:37:03.419 --> 00:37:04.460
They're already built in.

00:37:04.460 --> 00:37:06.293
So you don't need to
add the roles on there.

00:37:06.293 --> 00:37:08.210
And the browsers support
it reasonably well.

00:37:08.210 --> 00:37:12.120
So if I do a generic
desktop layout,

00:37:12.120 --> 00:37:14.720
there they all are, the footer,
the header, the main, the nav.

00:37:14.720 --> 00:37:16.750
They're there.

00:37:16.750 --> 00:37:19.770
If you were to view
it mobile-- and I

00:37:19.770 --> 00:37:21.710
say mobile because
in responsive design,

00:37:21.710 --> 00:37:23.085
it usually just
means linearizing

00:37:23.085 --> 00:37:24.580
for a narrow screen.

00:37:24.580 --> 00:37:27.220
Same stuff, just use
the right elements.

00:37:27.220 --> 00:37:29.140
They've already got
the stuff built in.

00:37:29.140 --> 00:37:31.180
You don't need to
rely on the roles.

00:37:31.180 --> 00:37:34.247
ARIA isn't needed, because
it's already there.

00:37:34.247 --> 00:37:35.080
Leave the roles out.

00:37:35.080 --> 00:37:37.350
You're good to go.

00:37:37.350 --> 00:37:41.430
HTML5 headings-- a lot of people
will navigate by headings.

00:37:41.430 --> 00:37:42.240
Go in order.

00:37:42.240 --> 00:37:44.240
Don't skip around.

00:37:44.240 --> 00:37:47.340
h1, h2, h3, step
back out of it OK.

00:37:47.340 --> 00:37:49.590
Don't go h1, h2, h4.

00:37:49.590 --> 00:37:53.080
You're creating some confusion
for a user at that point.

00:37:53.080 --> 00:37:55.610
There is no document
outline algorithm.

00:37:55.610 --> 00:37:57.640
It's mentioned in
the specification,

00:37:57.640 --> 00:37:59.570
but no browser supports it.

00:37:59.570 --> 00:38:02.750
So if anybody's telling you
that the document outline

00:38:02.750 --> 00:38:04.950
algorithm is something
that needs to be supported,

00:38:04.950 --> 00:38:07.590
which is every time you do a
section you put an h1 in it,

00:38:07.590 --> 00:38:09.450
for example, ignore that.

00:38:09.450 --> 00:38:11.740
Just follow good
heading structure.

00:38:15.000 --> 00:38:19.120
Section and article are often
misused as generic containers,

00:38:19.120 --> 00:38:20.250
and they are not.

00:38:20.250 --> 00:38:22.790
Those can overwhelm users
of assistive technology,

00:38:22.790 --> 00:38:25.796
because they're just
thrown all over the page.

00:38:25.796 --> 00:38:27.170
My rule of thumb
is unless you're

00:38:27.170 --> 00:38:29.610
going to put a heading
in there in h1 through 6,

00:38:29.610 --> 00:38:30.820
then don't make it a section.

00:38:30.820 --> 00:38:31.986
Don't make an article there.

00:38:31.986 --> 00:38:33.200
It's unnecessary.

00:38:33.200 --> 00:38:35.410
If you need a
container for styling,

00:38:35.410 --> 00:38:37.280
use a div-- no big deal.

00:38:40.710 --> 00:38:45.190
Virgin America website has been
hailed as a really good design.

00:38:45.190 --> 00:38:48.470
There is no indicator anywhere
on the page where I am.

00:38:48.470 --> 00:38:50.230
As I tab through
this page, I have

00:38:50.230 --> 00:38:53.060
no sense of what's
going on, of where I am.

00:38:53.060 --> 00:39:00.000
It's a simple, simple fix
and an absurd oversight.

00:39:00.000 --> 00:39:01.540
You need to have
the focus styles.

00:39:01.540 --> 00:39:04.370
Keyboard users can't use
your site or your software

00:39:04.370 --> 00:39:06.414
without them.

00:39:06.414 --> 00:39:07.830
If you already
have a hover style,

00:39:07.830 --> 00:39:10.230
a colon hover,
put a colon focus.

00:39:10.230 --> 00:39:12.620
Match the selector, put focus.

00:39:12.620 --> 00:39:14.850
If you are using
libraries, see if they

00:39:14.850 --> 00:39:16.650
have focus styles in them.

00:39:16.650 --> 00:39:21.230
And if they do, look for the
outline none and remove it.

00:39:21.230 --> 00:39:24.040
You'd be amazed at how
removing that one line of CSS

00:39:24.040 --> 00:39:26.960
makes a whole lot of
sites and applications

00:39:26.960 --> 00:39:28.300
suddenly conformant.

00:39:28.300 --> 00:39:30.890
Suddenly they're usable
again just by removing that.

00:39:33.722 --> 00:39:34.680
See, we're almost done.

00:39:34.680 --> 00:39:36.710
This is actually perfect.

00:39:36.710 --> 00:39:40.640
Alternative text on
images-- do use it.

00:39:40.640 --> 00:39:43.740
Use it every opportunity you
have where it makes sense.

00:39:43.740 --> 00:39:45.870
In particular,
think about images

00:39:45.870 --> 00:39:49.220
where the image contains
a lot of content.

00:39:49.220 --> 00:39:51.170
Think about
infographics, probably

00:39:51.170 --> 00:39:54.910
the most inaccessible
form of graphic expression

00:39:54.910 --> 00:39:56.690
we have right now on the web.

00:39:56.690 --> 00:39:59.370
An infographic can't be
read by a screen reader,

00:39:59.370 --> 00:40:01.730
and alt text is usually
insufficient in order

00:40:01.730 --> 00:40:03.510
to convey what's in there.

00:40:03.510 --> 00:40:07.830
There is an attribute in
HTML called Long Desk.

00:40:07.830 --> 00:40:11.500
Also, ARIA-describedat
is the ARIA equivalent.

00:40:11.500 --> 00:40:15.300
And all you do is you provide
a URL to a longer description.

00:40:15.300 --> 00:40:19.470
And in the image here, I
have a pretty large graphic

00:40:19.470 --> 00:40:22.310
on the left, and on the
right I have the full text

00:40:22.310 --> 00:40:25.714
transcription of everything
that's going on in the image.

00:40:25.714 --> 00:40:27.630
When I did that, that
links to a separate page

00:40:27.630 --> 00:40:30.130
that held all of my
long descriptions.

00:40:30.130 --> 00:40:32.106
Since then, some
research has been

00:40:32.106 --> 00:40:33.480
done that shows
that users really

00:40:33.480 --> 00:40:36.140
prefer keeping that long
description on the same page

00:40:36.140 --> 00:40:37.670
so that you're not sending
them to another page,

00:40:37.670 --> 00:40:39.378
and then they have to
hit the back button

00:40:39.378 --> 00:40:41.650
and load the page two
more times in total.

00:40:41.650 --> 00:40:43.820
But it's pretty easy
to write that out,

00:40:43.820 --> 00:40:46.857
and I'm speaking-- this
is going to sound weird,

00:40:46.857 --> 00:40:49.190
but if you're a company that
worries about search engine

00:40:49.190 --> 00:40:51.380
optimization, for
example, it's a great way

00:40:51.380 --> 00:40:54.830
to get some valid keywords in
there without keyword stuffing.

00:40:54.830 --> 00:40:57.516
If anybody in the
